:::summary
Marco Polo (c. 1254–1324) was a Venetian merchant and traveler whose 24-year journey across the Silk Road to the court of Kublai Khan in China opened European eyes to the wealth, sophistication, and vastness of the Far East. His account, *The Travels of Marco Polo*, dictated while he was imprisoned in Genoa, became the most important geographical text of the medieval period and directly inspired the Age of Exploration — Columbus himself carried a copy on his first voyage.
:::

